				<H2 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:1.0em;">When should a Floor be replaced?</h2>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					There are many signs that it is time to <strong>replace</strong> your <strong>Floor</strong>. Missing shingles, cracked or curling shingles, blistering or peeling paint, damaged flashing, your <strong>Floor</strong> is rotting,  leakage on the attic after heavy rains, Stains on interior walls or ceilings, High energy bills. Any one of these could be an indication that it is time to install a <strong>new Floor.</strong>
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					Also, you should find out how long your current <strong>Floor</strong> has been on your home.  A <strong>Floor</strong> life ranges anywhere from 15- 50 years depending on which shingle you had installed on your Floor. Ask one of our <strong></strong>Flooring contractors</strong> to determine the life of your Floor.  
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;" align="center">
		<a href="http://www.certainteed.com/products/Flooring"><img src="img/Floor-certainteed.gif" alt="Certainteed Flooring " width="151" height="57" border="0"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="http://www.fabral.com/residential.php"><img src="img/fabral-logo.gif" alt="Flooring contractor Floorer companies" width="181" height="87" border="0"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.tamko.com/HomeownerHomeLandingPage/tabid/117/Default.aspx"><img src="img/Floor-tamko.gif" alt="Floorers Flooring" width="151" height="57" border="0"></a>
	</p>
					
					<H2 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:1.0em;">Choose the right Floor and Floor color for your home.</h2>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					If your <strong>replacement Floor</strong> is low pitched <strong>Floor</strong>, you may not have a choice in the <strong>Flooring</strong> material used.  J.M.Grove and the manufacturers recommend that EPDM rubber Floor be installed on Flat Floors. <a href="Flooring-shingles.php">Rubber Floors</a> are one of the most common types of low-slope Flooring materials. This is because it is relatively inexpensive, simple to install, and fairly clean to work with when compared to conventional built-up Floors. There aren't the odors and fumes that accompany built-up Floors which appeals to many property owners.
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					If your <strong>Floor</strong> is pitched then you can choose from a variety of pre-approved Flooring materials by Grove. Asphalt <strong>Floor</strong>, shake & composite shake <strong>Floor</strong>, slate & composite slate <strong>Floor</strong>, and standing seam <strong>metal Floor</strong> to name a few. Choosing the right material on your <strong>Floor</strong>, you should consider the look you want for your home, the life expectancy you desire and the price. 
					</p>
					<div style="width:100%">
					<ul style="padding: 0px 15px 3px 200px;  font-size:.8em;; float:left;list-style-image: url(img/bullet-splash.gif);">
