					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					The color chosen should compliment your houses decor. Matching your <strong>Floor</strong> with the siding or using the same color as your previous <strong>Floor</strong> is a good way to choose your Floor's color. When choosing a <strong>Floor</strong> color, you should be advised that the lighter the color the longer your shingles will last. Speak with our <strong>Flooring contractors</strong> to pick the perfect <strong>Flooring</strong> option for your home. 
					</p>
					
					<H2 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:1.0em;">How long does it take to replace a Floor?</h2>
					
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					<strong>Replacing a Floor</strong>, whether on a commercial or residential building, is a labor-intensive project and, depending on the type of <strong>Floor</strong>, could take a <strong>Flooring company</strong> anywhere from a few days to 2 or more weeks, depending on the size and difficulty of installing shingles on your Floor. The time involved is substantially affected by the weather, as well. Wind, snow, rain, or even just the threat of one of these and will slow the process considerably. For built-up Floors, removing and replacing the Floor will probably proceed at a rate of approximately 1,500 square feet per day. For single-ply Floors, the rate is closer to 2,000 to 4,000 square feet per day. 
					</p>
					<H2 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:1.0em;">Getting the full life span out of your Floor</h2>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					J.M. Grove recommends proper ventilation should be applied with your <strong>new Floor</strong>. Allowing moisture to escape from your Floor will drastically improve your Floors life. Proper ventilation will remove moisture and heat from the attic. Trapped heat and moisture can raise energy costs, cause ice dams, and damage Floor system components as well as structural and personal items located inside the attic where temperatures can easily reach 150 F degrees. Condensation that forms inside attics can be caused by the use of washing machines, dish washers, bath tubs, showers, and tumble driers and damage the integrity of the Floor unless these items are properly ventilated. Proper ventilation can also decrease the amount of <strong>Floor repairs</strong> necessary throughout the life of your Floor
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					<img src="img/Floor-inspection.gif" alt="Floor inspection" width="290" height="300" border="0"align="right">Ice and water shield is a self-adhered protective membrane that sits between the shingles and Floor deck, providing Floors ultimate protection against the elements. Ice and water shields should be installed on all the edges of your Floor and around any penetration points (i.e., chimney, skylights etc) to prevent water damage caused by ice dams. Ice and water shield give an extra layer of protection around the most vulnerable sections of your Floor, it is highly recommended.
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					J.M. Grove recommends preventative maintenance <strong>Floor repairs</strong> every five years to prevent costly repairs before they happen for your Floor. Grove has a 21 point inspection list that includes caulking, checking for penetration points, fixing any loose shingles and repairing fish hooks to name a few. Preventative maintenance can prevent leaks and costly damages to your home before they happen.
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					Apply these tips to your home and you will get the full life expectancy out of your Floor and save yourself money!
					</p>
					
					<H2 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:1.0em;">Recognizing common signs that your Floor needs to be replaced</h2>
					
					<H3 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.9em;">Missing Floor shingles</h3>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					If your Floor is fairly new and you are missing shingles, either the nails fastening the shingle down came loose, or high winds caused the shingle to come loose. In this situation a minor <strong>Floor repair</strong> should be applied to replace the missing shingles. This should be done ASAP to prevent any moisture from entering your house and possibly rotting any wood. Rotted wood can be very expensive, save time and money and replace your Floor shingles before any rotting can occur.
					</p>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					If your Floor is outlived its life span and there are many shingles missing all over your Floor. It is recommended install a <strong>new Floor</strong>. Service calls to repair your Floor will only cost extra and will only temporarily fix the problem.
					</p>
					<H3 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.9em;">Floor rotting</h3>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					<img src="img/Floor- rott.gif" alt="Floorers" width="146" height="96" border="0"align="right">Rotting is a sign that your shingles have outlived its life span. It is recommended to <strong>install a new Floor</strong> as soon as possible before moisture can cause the framing of your house to rot. Wood rotting can be very expensive and damage your home immensely.
					</p>
					<H3 style="padding: 10px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.9em;">Wet spots on your ceiling</h3>
					<p style="padding: 0px 20px 10px 20px;font-size:.8em;">
					<img src="img/Floor-stain_r2_c2.gif" alt="Floorers Flooring" width="146" height="96" border="0"align="left">If you notice stain marks on your ceiling, this is a sign that your Floor is leaking. Contact us as soon as possible for an emergency repair. The moisture entering your home can cause costly damages to your Floor and your personal property. Don't let the problem get any worse than it already has. Your Floor might just need a minor repair or it might need to be replaced with a new Floor. Click request a repair or call us (717) 669-1930 to fix your leak.
							
